Optical discs are designed to store and distribute digital data. The first optical disc was developed by IBM in the late 1960s and was known as the Laservision. This system used an analog signal written onto the surface of a 12-inch vinyl disc. In the late 1970s, the first compact discs (CDs) were developed. These discs used a digital signal and could store up to 80 minutes of audio data.In the late 1980s, DVDs were developed to store more data than CDs. DVDs could hold up to 8.5 GB of data and began to